    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's weather has a clear annual pattern, and it matters more to a sale campaign than many sellers realise. From late October through to March, the region moves into the wet season: afternoon storms, heavier and more frequent rainfall, the occasional ex-tropical cyclone weakening down the coast, and, in the worst years, localised flooding. The March 2022 rainfall event and the 2011 flood are still in recent memory for Brisbane buyers, and the conversation about flooding, stormwater, and weather resilience is part of every serious property discussion in the inner east.</p>

      <p>For sellers, this creates a real set of campaign questions. Does the weather itself reduce buyer attendance? Does a rainy open home hurt the result? What do you do when a major storm hits mid-campaign? How do you handle the flood conversation honestly without scaring off buyers who would otherwise be comfortable? What does good presentation look like when the garden is waterlogged and the grass is too wet to mow? And what are the insurance and contract implications if damage occurs between contract signing and settlement?</p>

      <p>This article walks through those questions. Brisbane sellers frequently assume the wet months are bad for selling and delay campaigns as a result. The reality is more nuanced: the wet season has its own opportunities and its own traps, and a well-prepared campaign can perform strongly through November to March if the right steps are taken.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The myth that rain kills sales</h2>
      <p>The conventional wisdom is that nobody buys a house in a downpour. As with most conventional wisdom, there is a grain of truth and a lot of exaggeration. Yes, open home attendance drops when the forecast is bad. A storm on a Saturday morning might cut attendance by 30 to 50% at a typical open home. But attendance is not the metric that matters for a seller. What matters is qualified buyer engagement, and the relationship between bad weather and qualified buyers is much weaker than the relationship between bad weather and casual browsers.</p>

      <p>Serious buyers who have already been watching the market, already done their research, and already decided they want to see the property will generally turn up regardless of weather. Casual browsers who might have stopped in on a sunny Saturday afternoon will stay home. The buyer mix at a wet-weather open home is therefore typically higher quality than at a sunny one, even if the total number is lower. Offers and sale outcomes frequently come from these smaller, more serious crowds.</p>

      <p>Brisbane-based agents with long track records in wet season campaigns consistently report that strong offers often come from buyers who first inspected in poor weather. The reason is partly self-selection (only the genuinely interested turn up), and partly that a well-presented property in wet conditions actually looks impressive: you can see that the drainage works, the roof is sound, the covered outdoor area is usable even in a storm, and the interior stays dry and comfortable. Buyers come away reassured, not deterred.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presentation during the wet season</h2>
      <p>The visual presentation of a property in wet weather is a real challenge, but there are several practical steps that experienced vendors take to ensure the property still shows well.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Get the photography done before the weather breaks.</strong> In Brisbane, the window for strong listing photography is typically late August to mid-October, when skies are clear, gardens are green, and natural light is at its best. If you are planning a November or December campaign, book photography for late October so you have dry-weather hero images ready for the portals. A listing's first impression online is almost always the first photo, and if that photo was taken in a downpour, the click-through rate drops.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Invest in interior presentation.</strong> When exterior visuals are compromised by weather, the interior becomes the star of the campaign. Stylists, lighting, and cleanliness matter more than usual. A well-styled living room with warm lighting on a wet Brisbane Saturday is genuinely appealing. A damp-smelling hallway with water marks on the entry floor is the opposite.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Manage the outdoor spaces carefully.</strong> Covered outdoor areas (decks, patios, pergolas) become disproportionately important during the wet months because they are one of the few exterior features that remain usable. Stage them as outdoor rooms, not as spaces that happen to have a roof. Cushions, heat lamps on cool nights, and small lighting touches make a covered deck look like a year-round asset rather than a summer-only feature.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Lawn and garden maintenance in wet weather.</strong> Mowing a waterlogged lawn does not work, and a waterlogged lawn does not photograph well. Plan ahead: if a storm is forecast before an open home, have the lawn mowed the day before the rain, and allow it to drain. Clear leaf litter and branches before the open home starts. A garden that looks tidy in the rain is not the same as a garden that looks tidy in the sun, but it can still look cared-for.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Interior moisture control.</strong> Humidity rises sharply in wet Brisbane weeks, and that produces subtle problems for open homes: damp-smelling rooms, condensation on windows, slow-drying laundry areas, mould risk in bathrooms with poor ventilation. Run dehumidifiers in closed rooms for the 24 hours before an open home. Open windows and use exhaust fans in the bathrooms. A subtle smell of moisture is one of the fastest ways to make a property feel unloved, even if the rest of the presentation is strong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Open home logistics in storm conditions</h2>
      <p>Wet weather open homes require more planning than dry weather ones. A few practical points.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Entry management.</strong> Set up a proper entry system: a covered or sheltered walk from the street or driveway to the front door, a large entry mat, a shoe rack, and a stand for wet umbrellas. If the open home is on a rainy day and the entry is not prepared, the floors inside will be wet and slippery within 15 minutes and the property will smell like damp carpet by the end of the open home.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Clear communication with buyers.</strong> If the forecast is severe, the agent should communicate proactively with registered and expected attendees. Let them know the open home is going ahead, that the property shows well in wet conditions, and that the entry is prepared. This reduces no-shows and signals that the campaign is professionally managed.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Private inspections as a backup.</strong> For serious buyers who cannot or will not attend an open home in bad weather, a private inspection option keeps the campaign momentum intact. Agents who are flexible on mid-week or evening private inspections during storm weeks often capture offers that would otherwise have been lost.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Safety considerations.</strong> In severe weather warnings (Bureau of Meteorology storm or cyclone warnings), it is reasonable and sometimes necessary to postpone an open home. The agent should make this call in consultation with the seller, and the postponement should be communicated as a safety decision rather than a weather avoidance. Most buyers are understanding, and the rescheduled open home often benefits from improved weather.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The flood conversation, honestly</h2>
      <p>For many Brisbane inner-east properties, flood history is a live topic for buyers. The 2011 and 2022 floods affected specific suburbs more than others, and the conversation is particularly pointed for properties in known overland flow paths or close to the Brisbane River. Sellers of flood-affected properties sometimes hope the topic will not come up. It will.</p>

      <p>The best approach is to address flood history openly, with context. This means disclosing any flood impact to the property (past water levels, any damage, and any remediation works done), distinguishing between river flooding and overland flow (the two are often confused and have different risk profiles), and pointing to the current state of the property. Flood maps from Brisbane City Council are publicly available and sophisticated buyers consult them. Pretending flood risk does not exist is not a viable strategy in 2027.</p>

      <p>Sellers of flood-affected properties who have invested in mitigation (drainage improvements, raised services, resilient materials on lower levels) should document what has been done and make that documentation available to buyers. A property that was affected in 2011 but has been remediated and has performed well through 2022 and subsequent weather events has a genuine story, and buyers will often accept the risk with that context. A property with a flood history and no documented remediation is a harder sell, but still saleable at the right price and with honest disclosure.</p>

      <p>For properties with no flood history, the conversation is simpler but still requires care. Saying "this property has never flooded" is a fact statement that can be verified, and it is better than vague reassurance. Combining that with recent council flood map data and (where relevant) insurance quotes that confirm a low risk rating gives buyers the factual basis they need.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Storm damage during a campaign</h2>
      <p>Severe storms do occasionally cause damage to properties during active sale campaigns. Hail damage to roofs, fallen trees, broken windows, and localised water ingress are all possibilities. Sellers need to know how these events affect the campaign.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Before contract.</strong> If damage occurs before a contract is signed, the seller's insurance covers the repair (subject to the policy) and the agent manages the campaign disruption. Open homes may need to be paused for a week or two while repairs are completed. Photography may need to be refreshed. Portal listings may need to be updated if the damage is visible in exterior shots. The campaign continues, but with a temporary slowdown.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">After contract, before settlement.</strong> Queensland's standard contract places the risk of damage between contract signing and settlement on the seller (this is different from some other jurisdictions). The seller is responsible for delivering the property in substantially the same condition it was in at contract signing. If significant damage occurs during this window, the buyer may have a right to terminate or to a reduction in price; the exact rights depend on the extent of damage. Seller insurance remains important through this period, and sellers should confirm their policy covers this window.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">The role of the solicitor.</strong> Any storm damage during contract requires immediate communication with the seller's solicitor. Small damage is usually handled through repairs before settlement, with no contract impact. Larger damage can trigger contract-level issues that need careful management. The solicitor coordinates between insurer, repairer, and buyer's solicitor to keep the contract on track.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Insurance during a wet-season sale</h2>
      <p>A few specific insurance points are worth confirming before launching a wet-season campaign.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Home and contents.</strong> Confirm your home insurance is current and covers storm and flood damage. Many policies distinguish between storm damage, flood damage, and actions of the sea, and some owners discover at the worst possible moment that they have the wrong coverage. If you are selling an investment property, confirm landlord insurance is current.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Public liability for open homes.</strong> If a buyer slips on a wet floor at an open home and injures themselves, they may have a claim against the seller. Standard home insurance policies typically cover this, but confirm the coverage before listing. Your agent should also have professional indemnity and public liability coverage for their role in the campaign.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Contract-period coverage.</strong> Because Queensland places pre-settlement risk on the seller, confirm your insurance covers you through to settlement day. If settlement is delayed (which sometimes happens during wet season for weather-related reasons), the insurance needs to extend through the actual settlement date, not just the planned one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Is November to March a bad time to sell in Brisbane?</h2>
      <p>The short answer: no, not inherently, provided the campaign is prepared for wet-season conditions. There are specific advantages to selling in this window.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Less competition.</strong> Many vendors hold off listing during the wet months, which reduces the supply of listings and therefore increases the attention available to the properties that are on the market. For a well-presented home, this can actually produce stronger buyer engagement than a Spring campaign in a crowded field.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Serious buyer pool.</strong> Wet season buyers are typically more committed. They are searching because they need to, not because they are idly browsing on sunny weekends. An interested buyer in December is often a more qualified buyer than one in October.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Relocation and end-of-year timing.</strong> Buyers moving to Brisbane for January job starts, school enrolments, or end-of-year life changes tend to be active in the November to December window. They are motivated, they have a timeline, and they make decisions.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Weather resilience as a selling point.</strong> A property that shows well in wet conditions (covered outdoor space, good drainage, sound roof, dry interior) is actively selling its weather resilience during each inspection. Buyers who see a property perform well in storms often become more confident about the purchase than they would have on a sunny day.</p>

      <p>The disadvantages are real but manageable. Photography is harder to get right. Open home attendance is more variable. Storm events can interrupt campaigns for a week or more. Flood conversations are front of mind. But none of these are campaign killers, and experienced Brisbane agents run strong wet-season campaigns every year.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical wet-season campaign checklist</h2>
      <p>Before launching a November to March campaign, confirm the following are in place.</p>

      <p>1. Photography booked and completed in clear weather, ideally in October. 2. Interior presentation prioritised: stylist engaged, lighting refreshed, humidity managed. 3. Covered outdoor areas styled as year-round rooms. 4. Lawn and garden plan adjusted for wet conditions, with a maintenance schedule around forecast rainfall. 5. Entry management plan for open homes: covered walkway, large mat, umbrella stand, shoe rack. 6. Agent plan for severe weather postponement, with clear communication protocols. 7. Flood history and remediation documentation ready for disclosure. 8. Insurance confirmed: home, contents, public liability, and coverage through to settlement. 9. Contract and disclosure pack prepared in advance so storm disruptions do not delay buyer decisions. 10. Backup inspection options (private, evening, or mid-week) available for buyers who cannot attend a scheduled open home due to weather.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's wet season is not a reason to delay a sale campaign. It is a reason to prepare one more carefully. Serious buyers are active through November to March. Competition from other listings is often lighter than in Spring. A well-presented property that performs well in wet conditions is effectively demonstrating its weather resilience to every buyer who inspects it. The right preparation (dry-weather photography, strong interior presentation, clear flood disclosure, good open home logistics, and proper insurance coverage) produces campaigns that compete with or outperform Spring launches in the same market. For many inner-east Brisbane homes, particularly family homes with covered outdoor areas and sound drainage, the wet season is actually a strong window rather than a weak one.</p>

